author: Al Jazeera English
description:
African nations are calling for justice and accountability for colonial-era crimes in the form of reparations.
Algeria suggests a legal framework to hold former occupiers accountable. 
Instead, France has opted for 'symbolic acts' that promote reconciliation.
Britain has paid almost $20 million in compensation to more than 5,000 Kenyans abused by the colonial administration. 
And Germany has agreed to pay Namibia $1.1 billion in development aid over 30 years. 
But with the continent as a whole still paying a heavy price for colonialism, which other African countries should receive reparations? 
And can the cost of colonial-era abuses be measured?

Presenter: Bernard Smith

Guests:
Abdelkader Abderrahmane -- Independent researcher and co-author of 'The Politics of Algeria'

Liliane Umubyeyi -- Co-Founder and Executive Director of African Futures Lab

Nicolas Normand -- Former French ambassador to Mali, the Republic of Congo/Congo-Brazzaville and Senegal

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Pope Leo XIV has concluded his three-day visit to Lebanon - wrapping up his first international trip as leader of the Catholic Church. 
The Pontiff has offered prayers at the site of the 2020 Beirut port blast, one of the final stops in his three-day visit to Lebanon.
The Catholic leader prayed silently and lit a lamp on Tuesday morning at a monument to the more than 220 people that were killed and 6,500 injured in the explosion. The United States-born pontiff has urged peaceful coexistence across the Middle East during his inaugural trip abroad.
With mounds of rubble and the remains of the devastated facility within sight, the Pope shook hands, blessed and spoke with each one of the survivors and relatives of victims who were present.
“We are very grateful for this visit from the Pontiff,” said Cecile Roukoz, a lawyer whose brother died in the explosion. “We know that he raises his voice” for justice “and we need justice for our brothers and all the victims of this explosion”.

Al Ja
title: Pope Leo wraps up Lebanon visit with prayers at site of Beirut port blast

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Eagle Mujinga manages workers at Shabara cobalt mine in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC). As the world's biggest producer of cobalt, the DRC is a part of the chain that fuels electric vehicles and renewable energy worldwide. Miners in the DRC face dangerous working conditions and earn, on average, a few dollars per day to supply the multibillion-dollar industry.

Eagle is caught in the middle when unrest grows among miners who accuse foreign buyers of underweighing and undervaluing the cobalt they extract. Once a miner himself, can Mujinga navigate demands from the miners while maintaining relations with foreign buyers?

Cobalt Miners is a documentary film by Arthur Nazaryan, Neild Brandvold, Mike Shum and Qinling Li.

Japan–China tensions have led to multiple Japanese cultural events in China being abruptly cancelled.
Singer Maki Otsuki was escorted offstage in Shanghai, with organisers blaming “unavoidable circumstances”.
Concerts by Ayumi Hamasaki and Yuzu were also halted, angering fans and promoters.
The cancellations follow remarks by Japanese PM Sanae Takaichi suggesting Japan could intervene militarily if China attacked Taiwan.
Beijing has demanded she retract the comments, accusing Japan of being “evasive and obstinate”.
China has since banned Japanese seafood, frozen youth exchanges, and restricted flights and film releases.
Analysts warn Japanese cultural exports may face long-term damage if the dispute deepens.

Al Jazeera’s Katrina Yu reports from Beijing.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
South Africa's government recently classified gender-based violence as a national disaster.
The United Nations says the rate of femicide, intentional killing with a gender-related motivation, is more than five times the global average.

Police statistics show more than 5,500 women were murdered in South Africa in a year.
That’s an average of 15 women killed every single day.
The rate of sexual violence and assault is also high. 
More than 100 rapes are reported to the police daily and experts say the crime is underreported by as much as 95 percent.

Activists say the problem lies with poor implementation of legislation to protect women.
The case of 31-year-old Gaby Ndaba is one example.
She went missing in Johannesburg in May 2023.
Her body was discovered several days later, and the investigation is still ongoing. 
Here’s her story, told by her sister.

As with other special elections this year, Democrats are hoping to capitalise on discontent with Donald Trump.  

Al Jazeera’s Shihab Rattansi reports.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
More than a thousand people have been killed in floods and landslides across Indonesia, Sri Lanka and Thailand. 
Rescue efforts are taking place in some of the most difficult conditions, with hundreds still missing. 
The death toll in Indonesia alone has gone past 600 and nearly as many are missing.
The military has been deployed to some of the worst hit areas to join rescue efforts. 

Al Jazeera’s Jessica Washington reports from North Tapanuli, in the North Sumatra province, Indonesia.

description:
In Sri Lanka, the loss and damage from the flooding is the worst since the 2004 tsunami. 
At least 390 people have died and hundreds remain missing. 
Rescue and relief missions are underway across the country.

Al Jazeera’s Minelle Fernandez joined a rescue team in Kaduwela on the outskirts of Colombo, Sri Lanka.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Israeli forces have arrested at least 23 Palestinians across the occupied West Bank.
Troops entered dozens of homes, interrogating residents and damaging property.
Some of those detained were former prisoners.

These Israeli raids have caused a displacement crisis for Palestinians.
Hundreds of homes have been damaged or destroyed since January.
And there's no sign of a let-up in operations Israel says are aimed at clearing out Palestinian fighters.

Al Jazeera’s Ferdia Carr reports.

description:
US Special Envoy Steve Witkoff is to arrive in Moscow for a meeting with Vladimir Putin. 
The Kremlin’s confirmed that the negotiations will be held on Tuesday afternoon. 
The main topic is the US plan to resolve the military conflict in Ukraine, which has undergone serious changes in a little over a week. 

Al Jazeera’s Yulia Shapovalova reports from Moscow, Russia.
